originalText: ::Baritone.:: We are the last of our people in Lemuria. Me, my wife - and our daughter Synneva.

::Baritone.:: After the Great War, most prominent Native Lemurians arrived to Abyssal Station - most ministers, their families and everyone else who had been selected. All was well at the start: Biocorp never found this location, and the Natives integrated into the Subislander population well.
I don't know much about it myself, but from my understanding it's a highly valuable piece of technology from before the Great War.
All I know is that it's a pre-Great War technology that's somehow connected to certain machines capable of traversing great distances, even reaching the Surface. That's... beyond Outside.
Never mind. There was something else...
::Hoarse falsetto.:: Ehem, I believe it actually means "*sunken* land." It makes more sense, seeing that we live under water.
Todd seems to be exercising a lot.
Does Todd have a microchip implant in his hand?
Can you let Todd unlock the gate to R&D for me?

::Bass, appearing as though he wants to say something else but changes his mind instead.::

The Subislanders came to Lemuria way before the Great War and we've been together since.

::Baritone.:: There was no segregation, and the two peoples lived together, room to room. There was one place where the Natives didn't fit in: The Research and Development dome had two sections: General Laboratories section, and Special Laboratories section. The Special Laboratories performed highly advanced and specialized research, and were composed of respected Atlantean researchers who preferred working their own way and didn't like the outsiders.

Some of these were my great-grandparents, and everything I'm telling you now was passed down through the generations.
::Bass.:: I don't know anything about it, child. Hm, by the depths. If it's important, and if it's here... then it has to be at the Research and Development dome.

::Gentle falsetto.:: I think there is a kind of fish or a crustacean called lemur. These either lived here when your ancestors first came, or were named so because they were bred by Lemurians themselves.

originalText: Disunion didn't seem to have gotten in the way of good relations between you and the Subislanders?

Todd's problems... at first I thought it was Synneva, that, ehem, the problem was with her. But Stig convinced, convinced me that Todd... was the one who had fertility issues.

Todd and Synna always seemed like they were made for each other. They were so different yet so alike. They had no one else but each other, sure, but they are a perfect match. Our son needs our help. He's got so much to worry about and he can't possibly make time for everything. That's why I'm here. And my, ehem, husband, of course, and our in-laws.

Angus has always been a great father to Todd, great, we both are, hard-working and dedicated. It may seem like, ehem, he's hard on Todd, but, as I've told Stig and Asta many times, it's just how it comes across.

I do my best as a mother and wife and the only alimentary technician. I have to think about everything. But my mother has always taught me that to be strong you have to let it out. Let it out. So I have my boudoir where I can go and... weep, yes. It's nothing to be ashamed of. It releases negative emotions.

Most Subislanders went Outside during the Disunion, and the remaining ones continued living here with us. There was some tension in the succeeding years, naturally, but all was forgotten, yes. However, many lives were lost then, and much was destroyed.
There were a lot more Subislanders before the Disunion, yes, there were, but now... the Øivindrs are the only ones left.
